00:08:44.810 --> 00:08:47.600
And in particular, for those
who are not fully aware how

00:08:47.600 --> 00:08:52.160
math on webpages works, or
should work, I'll give a quick

00:08:52.160 --> 00:08:53.930
introduction on that now.

00:08:53.930 --> 00:08:58.170
So ideally, mathematics on the
web is represented by a

00:08:58.170 --> 00:09:00.630
special markup language
called MathML.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:03.100
MathML has been around
for some time.

00:09:03.100 --> 00:09:08.060
And it has evolved and matured
to a degree that it's now been

00:09:08.060 --> 00:09:14.240
made a stand for HTML5,
and as a consequence,

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:15.950
also for EPUB 3.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.290
So in other words, every EPUB
3 reader, in the future,

00:09:19.290 --> 00:09:21.830
should also be able to
deal with MathML.

00:09:21.830 --> 00:09:24.480
Now the question, of course,
arises, why is there a

00:09:24.480 --> 00:09:28.060
specialist markup language
just for mathematics.

00:09:28.060 --> 00:09:30.790
Well, the reason is that
mathematics is fairly

00:09:30.790 --> 00:09:37.390
involved, in terms of the way
expressions are being set up

00:09:37.390 --> 00:09:39.680
and how they're being
structured, which is normally

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:40.460
not doable--

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:42.180
or not easily doable--

00:09:42.180 --> 00:09:43.465
with just regular HTML.

00:09:43.465 --> 00:09:47.110
In particular, think about that
regular HTML is very good

00:09:47.110 --> 00:09:49.530
with dealing with text
and these things.

00:09:49.530 --> 00:09:51.310
It can also do sub
and superscript.

00:09:51.310 --> 00:09:54.980
However as soon as things become
more involved, as in a

00:09:54.980 --> 00:09:56.210
mathematics expression--

00:09:56.210 --> 00:10:00.260
which is, by nature, effectively
two dimensional

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:03.170
and very, very nested--

00:10:03.170 --> 00:10:06.520
HTML alone can normally
not deal with it.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:10.700
Therefore, MathML provides all
the basic functionality--

00:10:10.700 --> 00:10:13.600
or the basic tags--

00:10:13.600 --> 00:10:19.430
in order to create complex
mathematics expressions, and

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:21.130
display them on the web.

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:27.470
Now while it is, in general,
a good thing that MathML is

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:31.190
fairly mature, and that it's a
part of standards, what is a

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:36.390
drawback about MathML is that
it is not implemented in all

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:39.570
browsers, or all
EPUB 3 readers.

00:10:39.570 --> 00:10:43.360
As a consequence, there are
several ways of getting

00:10:43.360 --> 00:10:46.060
mathematics on the web
to work nevertheless.

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:53.180
So one of the ways it is done
by many sites, such as

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:59.140
Wikipedia, by default, as well
as other pages, is that one

00:10:59.140 --> 00:11:02.950
actually displays an image of
the mathematics instead of

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:05.530
having a MathML expression
in there.

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:09.760
And therefore, it can be easily
read by people who can

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:11.870
actually see the image.

00:11:11.870 --> 00:11:15.240
But it cannot necessarily be
picked up by a screen reader.

00:11:15.240 --> 00:11:20.820
Now the advantage of this is,
sometimes, that the real

00:11:20.820 --> 00:11:23.550
mathematics is still provided
somewhere in the background,

00:11:23.550 --> 00:11:24.620
not visible.

00:11:24.620 --> 00:11:27.710
And therefore, it can indeed
be used by screen reader.

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:30.730
And I'll demonstrate it to you
later, how that is being done.

00:11:30.730 --> 00:11:35.110
The other way of displaying
mathematics on all browsers on

00:11:35.110 --> 00:11:39.260
all platforms is by using a
little library called MathJax,

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:42.960
which is done by the
MathJax Consortium.

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:48.000
And if you want to check this
out, this is at mathjax.org.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:53.110
And the way this works is that
MathJax can be injected in any

00:11:53.110 --> 00:11:55.135
page that contents
mathematics.

00:11:55.135 --> 00:11:56.840
And it's JavaScript.

00:11:56.840 --> 00:11:59.870
And it just renders the
mathematics, which is either

00:11:59.870 --> 00:12:04.510
given as MathML or a more
traditional markup language

00:12:04.510 --> 00:12:06.960
like LaTeX or ASCIIMath.

00:12:06.960 --> 00:12:09.970
And it then renders
the mathematics.

00:12:09.970 --> 00:12:12.940
Now the challenge with this
process, for a screen reader

00:12:12.940 --> 00:12:15.850
who actually wants to use the
mathematics in order to speak

00:12:15.850 --> 00:12:18.180
it, is that we actually have to
deal with all these types

00:12:18.180 --> 00:12:20.800
of mathematics as
they can occur.

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:23.660
So we have to be able to deal
with just standard MathML

00:12:23.660 --> 00:12:27.460
expressions as well as
expressions rendered by

00:12:27.460 --> 00:12:31.100
MathJax, or expressions that are
just hidden somewhere, in

00:12:31.100 --> 00:12:34.760
an alternative text,
behind the image.

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:35.900
And I'll show you,
