Then, we have a little dot,
which separates the domain

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:56.840
name from the style name.

00:40:56.840 --> 00:40:57.760
And styles--

00:40:57.760 --> 00:41:03.430
again, we have styles like
short, verbose, or I think we

00:41:03.430 --> 00:41:05.890
also have super brief.

00:41:05.890 --> 00:41:09.470
But there is no limit to what
you want to call your style.

00:41:09.470 --> 00:41:11.980
If you want to call your style
after your personal name, then

00:41:11.980 --> 00:41:15.010
we'll have an additional style
in ChromeVox, in the future.

00:41:15.010 --> 00:41:17.350
And again, there is
a default style.

00:41:17.350 --> 00:41:20.410
Here, we're working, now, on
the default domain, and the

00:41:20.410 --> 00:41:22.370
style is short.

00:41:22.370 --> 00:41:23.290
All right.

00:41:23.290 --> 00:41:27.880
And then, the rest of the rule
is effectively a way how to

00:41:27.880 --> 00:41:32.230
test whether a rule is
applicable, plus the action

00:41:32.230 --> 00:41:34.300
the rule is supposed
to perform.

00:41:34.300 --> 00:41:38.000
In ChromeVox, this is given
the other way around.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:41.530
We first start with the action
and then with the

00:41:41.530 --> 00:41:47.550
precondition, or the part of
the rule that tests whether

00:41:47.550 --> 00:41:50.770
the actual rule is applicable.

00:41:50.770 --> 00:41:55.130
I'll tell you, in a second,
why this is the case.

00:41:55.130 --> 00:42:00.210
Let's first have a look at this
letter part, which talks

00:42:00.210 --> 00:42:04.410
about the precondition if
the rule is applicable.

00:42:04.410 --> 00:42:10.010
What we want is a node, which
is our fraction up here.

00:42:13.410 --> 00:42:19.660
This division node is given
by a MathML tag,

00:42:19.660 --> 00:42:21.560
which is called mfrac.

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:24.480
And we select this using an
XPath expression here.

00:42:24.480 --> 00:42:27.350
So this is a regular XPath
expression, which just says,

00:42:27.350 --> 00:42:30.320
well, the current node--
the node we are on--

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:35.940
is a node with an mfrac tag
in the MathML name space.

00:42:35.940 --> 00:42:40.550
So this is just a regular
XPath expression.

00:42:40.550 --> 00:42:44.050
Then, the rule will fire.

00:42:44.050 --> 00:42:46.420
And it will perform
it's action.

00:42:46.420 --> 00:42:47.500
So what are the Actions?

00:42:47.500 --> 00:42:51.680
Well, actions are a sequence
of components of different

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:53.240
things the rule does.

00:42:53.240 --> 00:42:55.910
In this case, we only have
one compartment.

00:42:55.910 --> 00:42:57.060
And that component is currently

00:42:57.060 --> 00:43:00.270
composed of two things--

00:43:00.270 --> 00:43:05.000
the type of the component,
as well as

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:07.550
what is being performed.

00:43:07.550 --> 00:43:09.330
So the type of the
component here is

00:43:09.330 --> 00:43:11.970
given in square brackets.

00:43:11.970 --> 00:43:15.880
In this case, the type is t,
which means it's just a text

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:18.160
that is being spoken.

00:43:18.160 --> 00:43:20.440
And the text that is being
spoken is then given as a

00:43:20.440 --> 00:43:24.500
string here, in string syntax,
with double quotes at the

00:43:24.500 --> 00:43:25.560
beginning and the end.

00:43:25.560 --> 00:43:29.430
So when we find the division
node, all we want, at this

00:43:29.430 --> 00:43:32.560
point, is a string being spoken
where it says, "some

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:36.440
division." Let's put
that rule in.

00:43:36.440 --> 00:43:38.440
And let's see what ChromeVox
says now.

00:43:38.440 --> 00:43:44.180
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division-- math.

00:43:44.180 --> 00:43:45.000
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:43:45.000 --> 00:43:46.870
That's all it says--
some division.

00:43:46.870 --> 00:43:48.260
x equals some division.

00:43:48.260 --> 00:43:50.580
We haven't specified
anything else.

00:43:50.580 --> 00:43:58.250
In particular, what we have not
specified here is how it

00:43:58.250 --> 00:44:01.820
should deal with any of the
other content that's still in

00:44:01.820 --> 00:44:02.990
the expression.

00:44:02.990 --> 00:44:04.710
So all we say at this
point is, say one

00:44:04.710 --> 00:44:07.150
string and then stop.

00:44:07.150 --> 00:44:09.551
Do not recurse any further.

00:44:09.551 --> 00:44:13.280
I'll show you, in a second, how
we can do that, otherwise.

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:16.440
Let's first talk a bit more
about the precondition.

00:44:16.440 --> 00:44:19.340
So the precondition here is an
XPath expression, as I said,

00:44:19.340 --> 00:44:21.690
that selects this particular
node--

00:44:21.690 --> 00:44:24.290
this particular node
with the mfrac tag.

00:44:24.290 --> 00:44:27.630
So it's this division node.

00:44:27.630 --> 00:44:31.350
Now in addition to this, one
can then give additional

00:44:31.350 --> 00:44:32.230
constraints.

00:44:32.230 --> 00:44:37.080
And the number of additional
constraints is unlimited.

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:41.170
Therefore, this is the reason
why we put the precondition at

00:44:41.170 --> 00:44:43.460
the end of this particular
rule definition.

00:44:43.460 --> 00:44:45.840
Because you can add more, and
more, and more, and more

00:44:45.840 --> 00:44:48.280
constraints to it.

00:44:48.280 --> 00:44:53.720
And I'll add one constraint,
just for you to be able to see

00:44:53.720 --> 00:44:54.980
what this will look like.

00:44:54.980 --> 00:44:58.050
So when we say, OK, so we want
this rule just to be

00:44:58.050 --> 00:45:04.930
applicable to something
that says that

00:45:04.930 --> 00:45:06.970
it's the node, itself.

00:45:06.970 --> 00:45:14.186
And it has a descendant, which
is an m square root.

00:45:14.186 --> 00:45:15.000
All right?

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.890
So that means it has a
descendant, which is a square

00:45:17.890 --> 00:45:20.950
root, up there.

00:45:20.950 --> 00:45:23.545
And again, this is in the
MathML name space.

00:45:28.650 --> 00:45:29.370
Right, sorry.

00:45:29.370 --> 00:45:33.300
Unexpected token means I have
forgotten to close my

00:45:33.300 --> 00:45:34.880
expression, my string
expression,

00:45:34.880 --> 00:45:38.010
with a square root.

00:45:38.010 --> 00:45:41.490
Let's see whether
it's applicable.

00:45:41.490 --> 00:45:45.520
Well, the thing is that we
haven't really changed any of

00:45:45.520 --> 00:45:46.020
the actions.

00:45:46.020 --> 00:45:49.040
So let's change the actions,
so we can actually hear

00:45:49.040 --> 00:45:53.030
whether the different rule
is being applied.

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:59.166
"--some division with
square root."

00:45:59.166 --> 00:46:07.280
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:46:07.280 --> 00:46:09.030
square root-- math.

00:46:09.030 --> 00:46:10.750
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:46:10.750 --> 00:46:12.830
So this has, indeed, worked.

00:46:15.990 --> 00:46:18.400
And it now applies
the other rule.

00:46:18.400 --> 00:46:21.710
So we have specialized the
rule even further.

00:46:21.710 --> 00:46:25.240
So in addition, we can now add
more and more constraints.

00:46:25.240 --> 00:46:28.780
Anything XPath1 allows you to
express, you can express in

00:46:28.780 --> 00:46:29.770
these constraints.

00:46:29.770 --> 00:46:31.140
And those are binary
constraints.

00:46:31.140 --> 00:46:34.930
So they only have
to hold, or not.

00:46:38.870 --> 00:46:39.100
Right.

00:46:39.100 --> 00:46:42.230
So this is as far as I want to
explain the preconditions.

00:46:42.230 --> 00:46:45.000
Now let's examine, a bit
further, what we can do in

00:46:45.000 --> 00:46:46.750
terms of the actions
of our rule.

00:46:46.750 --> 00:46:51.610
In particular, just having one
string pronounced, if you

00:46:51.610 --> 00:46:54.540
actually have a complex
expression, is usually not

00:46:54.540 --> 00:46:56.240
very fruitful.

00:46:56.240 --> 00:46:58.440
So we might want to have
a bit more pronounced.

00:46:58.440 --> 00:47:01.710
Therefore, let's dive into the
expression and pronounce some

00:47:01.710 --> 00:47:05.210
of the child nodes, actually.

00:47:05.210 --> 00:47:05.910
Right.

00:47:05.910 --> 00:47:08.580
So we now start a
new component.

00:47:08.580 --> 00:47:11.470
Components are being separated
by semicolons, so that's very

00:47:11.470 --> 00:47:15.320
similar to what you have
in regular JavaScript.

00:47:15.320 --> 00:47:19.190
And we now want to specify
a new component.

00:47:19.190 --> 00:47:21.460
And this is a particular
component which works on

00:47:21.460 --> 00:47:22.940
single nodes.

00:47:22.940 --> 00:47:25.500
So therefore, it gets
the type n.

00:47:25.500 --> 00:47:28.740
Again, the type is given
in square brackets.

00:47:28.740 --> 00:47:32.570
And now we can write a selector
which is just yet

00:47:32.570 --> 00:47:34.010
another XPath expression.

00:47:34.010 --> 00:47:39.160
So we write another XPath
selector that selects whatever

00:47:39.160 --> 00:47:43.720
child we want to work on,
or whatever node we

00:47:43.720 --> 00:47:44.350
want to work on.

00:47:44.350 --> 00:47:45.630
It doesn't necessarily
have to be a child.

00:47:45.630 --> 00:47:49.540
You can effectively also work
on any other node that is

00:47:49.540 --> 00:47:54.600
reachable from this particular
node you're on.

00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:56.680
But in our case, we want
to work on the child.

00:47:56.680 --> 00:47:58.470
But let's not work on both.

00:47:58.470 --> 00:48:01.090
Let's just work on the second
on, for instance.

00:48:01.090 --> 00:48:05.220
So this XPath expression, now,
just selects, from the given

00:48:05.220 --> 00:48:09.610
node, the second child node.

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:10.450
Right.

00:48:10.450 --> 00:48:13.820
And what the action now does
is it will pronounce the

00:48:13.820 --> 00:48:18.000
string "some division with
square root." And afterwards,

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:24.050
it will ask the speech rule
engine to recurse on this node

00:48:24.050 --> 00:48:25.948
that we have selected here.

00:48:25.948 --> 00:48:27.370
Let's do that again.

00:48:27.370 --> 00:48:31.920
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:48:31.920 --> 00:48:33.740
square root 2a--

00:48:33.740 --> 00:48:34.632
math.

00:48:34.632 --> 00:48:35.080
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:48:35.080 --> 00:48:38.570
So what you can hear is that we
heard the expression up to

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:39.520
the division.

00:48:39.520 --> 00:48:41.350
Then, it would pronounced
the string.

00:48:41.350 --> 00:48:46.630
And then, it would pronounce
the second child node.

00:48:46.630 --> 00:48:47.060
Right.

00:48:47.060 --> 00:48:52.110
Similarly, we could now
put in more content.

00:48:52.110 --> 00:48:57.570
So say we put in another
string of type t.

00:48:57.570 --> 00:49:00.300
Say this is now a string
called a numerator.

00:49:03.760 --> 00:49:07.970
And we now, for instance,
want to recurse on the

00:49:07.970 --> 00:49:11.530
first node, as well--

00:49:11.530 --> 00:49:15.630
on the first child as well,
not the first node.

00:49:15.630 --> 00:49:16.510
Let's do that.

00:49:16.510 --> 00:49:17.535
Let's listen to what's
happening.

00:49:17.535 --> 00:49:24.630
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:49:24.630 --> 00:49:28.190
square root 2a and
numerator minus b

00:49:28.190 --> 00:49:30.770
plus/minus square root--

00:49:30.770 --> 00:49:31.910
VOLKER SORGE: I'll
stop it here.

00:49:31.910 --> 00:49:33.770
We all know what the
numerator is.

00:49:33.770 --> 00:49:35.630
But you can see how
this now works.

00:49:35.630 --> 00:49:38.820
Now one of the things that David
pointed out earlier was

00:49:38.820 --> 00:49:43.810
that you can actually do changes
to the way the text to

00:49:43.810 --> 00:49:48.370
speech engine speaks things
from within a rule.

00:49:48.370 --> 00:49:49.810
And let's do that.

00:49:49.810 --> 00:49:54.090
The way this works is by
adding, in particular,

00:49:54.090 --> 00:49:57.410
annotations to each component.

00:49:57.410 --> 00:50:02.310
So for instance, say we want
to change the pitch on the

00:50:02.310 --> 00:50:06.310
first component that's
being spoken.

00:50:06.310 --> 00:50:09.220
Or in our case here, it's the
second component of the

00:50:09.220 --> 00:50:10.310
denominator.

00:50:10.310 --> 00:50:14.240
And let's say we just want to
have a significantly pitch

00:50:14.240 --> 00:50:17.390
change, say, to 1.5.

00:50:17.390 --> 00:50:20.870
Let's see how that sounds.

00:50:20.870 --> 00:50:24.580
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:50:24.580 --> 00:50:29.630
square root 2a and numerator
minus b plus--

00:50:29.630 --> 00:50:31.420
VOLKER SORGE: So you could
hear that the pitch was

00:50:31.420 --> 00:50:36.030
changed quite drastically when
the denominator of the

00:50:36.030 --> 00:50:37.860
division was being pronounced.

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:48.920
So the way we do these
annotations is by adding in

00:50:48.920 --> 00:50:54.560
round brackets, the particular
property we want to change, as

00:50:54.560 --> 00:50:56.980
well as the value
that changes it.

00:50:56.980 --> 00:50:57.610
All right.

00:50:57.610 --> 00:50:59.770
So in addition, we can, for
instance, also increase the

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:01.110
rate of the speech.

00:51:01.110 --> 00:51:03.940
Say we increase it to 2.5.

00:51:03.940 --> 00:51:06.710
And now let's see what's
being spoken now.

00:51:06.710 --> 00:51:09.940
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:51:09.940 --> 00:51:14.400
square root 2a and
numerator minus--

00:51:14.400 --> 00:51:16.120
VOLKER SORGE: That
was not really--

00:51:16.120 --> 00:51:16.770
That was--

00:51:16.770 --> 00:51:19.270
CHROMEVOX: Simple school
algebra, Volker Sorge, the

00:51:19.270 --> 00:51:21.100
third April, 2013

00:51:21.100 --> 00:51:23.360
VOLKER SORGE: Sorry, that was
not much of a change.

00:51:23.360 --> 00:51:27.610
I'll just refresh the console
so we can see a bit more.

00:51:27.610 --> 00:51:31.590
Let's try to change it to
something different.

00:51:31.590 --> 00:51:34.740
Maybe 0.5 will make
a difference.

00:51:34.740 --> 00:51:39.160
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:51:39.160 --> 00:51:42.450
square root 2a and
numerator minus--

00:51:42.450 --> 00:51:43.810
VOLKER SORGE: Now you could
hear that it was actually

00:51:43.810 --> 00:51:45.060
quite a bit faster.

00:51:50.100 --> 00:51:52.130
So what else can we
do with this?

00:51:52.130 --> 00:51:55.730
Well, another thing that we've
heard earlier was that we can

00:51:55.730 --> 00:52:01.270
add pauses to our rule.

00:52:01.270 --> 00:52:02.540
Let's do that as well.

00:52:02.540 --> 00:52:07.260
Let's add a pause annotation,
say, to the second--

00:52:07.260 --> 00:52:09.830
uh, no, to the first
of these--

00:52:13.210 --> 00:52:15.220
children that we speak.

00:52:15.220 --> 00:52:17.770
And let's add quite
a drastic pause.

00:52:17.770 --> 00:52:19.030
Pauses are given in
milliseconds.

00:52:19.030 --> 00:52:20.910
So let's add one second,
so we can actually

00:52:20.910 --> 00:52:23.270
hear it more clearly--

00:52:23.270 --> 00:52:26.874
so 1,000.

00:52:26.874 --> 00:52:31.020
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:52:31.020 --> 00:52:37.234
square root 2a and numerator
minus b--

00:52:37.234 --> 00:52:37.726
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:52:37.726 --> 00:52:43.830
So the effect you could hear
here was something I wanted to

00:52:43.830 --> 00:52:44.900
demonstrate.

00:52:44.900 --> 00:52:49.640
It is that the pause, as well as
all the other annotations--

00:52:49.640 --> 00:52:51.420
i.e. the pitch and the rate--

00:52:51.420 --> 00:52:56.320
than we give a particular node
here, or particular component,

00:52:56.320 --> 00:53:00.620
are recursively being applied
by the speech rule engine.

00:53:00.620 --> 00:53:04.650
That means if we change the
pitch somewhere, this pitch

00:53:04.650 --> 00:53:11.180
change will be propagated
further down in the recursive

00:53:11.180 --> 00:53:12.680
traversal of the tree.

00:53:12.680 --> 00:53:16.290
That means is we have nested
expressions, and we change the

00:53:16.290 --> 00:53:19.890
pitch several times, these
changes will add up, which

00:53:19.890 --> 00:53:22.177
gives a very nice effect
when it comes to

00:53:22.177 --> 00:53:23.140
pitch and rate changes.

00:53:23.140 --> 00:53:25.580
It doesn't really give a very
nice effect when it comes to

00:53:25.580 --> 00:53:26.540
pause changes.

00:53:26.540 --> 00:53:28.960
Because what that means is
that the pause is applied

00:53:28.960 --> 00:53:32.470
after every single element
that occurs.

00:53:32.470 --> 00:53:34.510
So you might want that.

00:53:34.510 --> 00:53:36.080
But you don't necessarily
want that.

00:53:36.080 --> 00:53:38.200
So in this particular
case, we don't.

00:53:38.200 --> 00:53:41.660
So how do we actually do it in
order to apply the pause

00:53:41.660 --> 00:53:46.260
between two chunks, rather
than having it applied

00:53:46.260 --> 00:53:48.840
recursively, during traversing
the tree?

00:53:48.840 --> 00:53:51.320
The way this works-- and I'll
show it to you here--

00:53:51.320 --> 00:53:56.430
is by adding the pause
explicitly as we recall a

00:53:56.430 --> 00:53:59.850
personality annotation,
which is another

00:53:59.850 --> 00:54:01.230
component of the actions.

00:54:01.230 --> 00:54:04.590
And this component
has the type p.

00:54:04.590 --> 00:54:06.300
So we put that in here.

00:54:06.300 --> 00:54:07.780
Let's get the bracketing
right.

00:54:07.780 --> 00:54:09.392
And let's see what
happens now.

00:54:12.104 --> 00:54:16.530
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:54:16.530 --> 00:54:21.694
square root 2a and numerator
minus b--

00:54:21.694 --> 00:54:22.161
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:54:22.161 --> 00:54:25.110
What you could hear now was that
the pause was actually

00:54:25.110 --> 00:54:30.180
only applied straight after
the denominator had been

00:54:30.180 --> 00:54:31.430
pronounced.

00:54:33.760 --> 00:54:34.290
Right.

00:54:34.290 --> 00:54:39.480
And in addition to this, we can
also, for instance, change

00:54:39.480 --> 00:54:40.730
the volume.

00:54:43.420 --> 00:54:44.850
But I'm not going
to demonstrate

00:54:44.850 --> 00:54:46.070
that now, in detail.

00:54:46.070 --> 00:54:48.610
Instead, I'm going to
demonstrate one final thing we

00:54:48.610 --> 00:54:53.590
can do with these speech rules,
and also, one final

00:54:53.590 --> 00:54:55.330
component--

00:54:55.330 --> 00:54:56.700
one type of component--

00:54:56.700 --> 00:54:58.930
for the action.

00:54:58.930 --> 00:55:02.160
And that is useful when you have
a node where you do not

00:55:02.160 --> 00:55:05.760
necessarily know how many
children the node has, and you

00:55:05.760 --> 00:55:10.280
want to recurse over
all these nodes.

00:55:10.280 --> 00:55:13.340
And we'll do that--

00:55:13.340 --> 00:55:14.590
give them our division here.

00:55:21.240 --> 00:55:21.540
Right.

00:55:21.540 --> 00:55:24.440
And this component is
of type m, which

00:55:24.440 --> 00:55:26.050
just stands for multinode.

00:55:26.050 --> 00:55:28.840
And you then give it
a set of nodes.

00:55:28.840 --> 00:55:32.120
In our case, we select the set
of nodes, again, with an XPath

00:55:32.120 --> 00:55:36.890
expression, which is
just all subnodes--

00:55:36.890 --> 00:55:40.620
or all child nodes-- of
our mfrac expression.

00:55:40.620 --> 00:55:41.430
Let's do that.

00:55:41.430 --> 00:55:42.450
Let's see what happens.

00:55:42.450 --> 00:55:46.310
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:55:46.310 --> 00:55:51.190
square root minus b plus/minus
square root of b

00:55:51.190 --> 00:55:55.290
square minus 4ac 2a--

00:55:55.290 --> 00:55:56.256
math.

00:55:56.256 --> 00:55:56.740
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:55:56.740 --> 00:56:01.330
So what you could hear now was
that all the elements are

00:56:01.330 --> 00:56:04.920
actually being pronounced
properly this time, in order,

00:56:04.920 --> 00:56:07.890
because this is just the regular
order within the

00:56:07.890 --> 00:56:11.050
MathML expression.

00:56:11.050 --> 00:56:14.320
Now obviously, for an expression
like division,

00:56:14.320 --> 00:56:17.430
where you really know that you
only have two children, this

00:56:17.430 --> 00:56:18.590
might not make a lot of sense.

00:56:18.590 --> 00:56:21.990
But if you do not know exactly
how many children there are--

00:56:21.990 --> 00:56:25.330
say, in the matrix expression
we've demonstrated earlier--

00:56:25.330 --> 00:56:29.960
you have to use this way off
accessing the children.

00:56:29.960 --> 00:56:32.840
And then you have, in addition,
the opportunity, or

00:56:32.840 --> 00:56:35.960
the possibility, to put in
something that is being spoken

00:56:35.960 --> 00:56:38.410
in between all of these
expressions.

00:56:38.410 --> 00:56:41.780
And the last thing I'll
demonstrate to you now is

00:56:41.780 --> 00:56:48.960
giving what we call a separator
string as a further

00:56:48.960 --> 00:56:52.190
annotation to our component.

00:56:52.190 --> 00:56:56.070
And the separator is just a
regular string, in this case.

00:56:56.070 --> 00:57:10.380
And let's just say, "divided
by," and spell it right, and

00:57:10.380 --> 00:57:12.452
see what happens now.

00:57:12.452 --> 00:57:16.350
CHROMEVOX: Given we have x
equals some division with

00:57:16.350 --> 00:57:22.710
square root minus b plus/minus
square root of b square minus

00:57:22.710 --> 00:57:26.240
4ac divided by 2a--

00:57:26.240 --> 00:57:27.500
math.

00:57:27.500 --> 00:57:28.340
VOLKER SORGE: Right.

00:57:28.340 --> 00:57:35.390
Back, we are, at the original
expression.

00:57:35.390 --> 00:57:35.870
Right.

00:57:35.870 --> 00:57:41.620
So this, so far, is the
explanation of this API.

00:57:41.620 --> 00:57:43.930
And why did we go into that
much detail in order to

00:57:43.930 --> 00:57:46.220
demonstrate to you how
this API works?

00:57:46.220 --> 00:57:50.210
Well, the basic idea of
ChromeVox is, since it is an

00:57:50.210 --> 00:57:53.760
open project, that we're
hoping that people will

00:57:53.760 --> 00:57:58.340
